02:49.545 --> 02:51.881
One thing we can all be grateful for

02:51.922 --> 02:53.549
is that we live in an age

02:53.591 --> 02:55.676
when we know that dead is dead.

03:08.147 --> 03:10.482
But modern medicine
has redefined the line

03:10.524 --> 03:12.276
between life and death.

03:16.196 --> 03:18.282
We now have control over that line

03:18.324 --> 03:20.326
in a way that previous generations

03:20.367 --> 03:22.202
would have considered miraculous

03:22.244 --> 03:24.455
or the work of the devil.

03:26.206 --> 03:28.542
Doctors routinely stop the heart

03:28.584 --> 03:30.502
during open heart surgery

03:30.544 --> 03:33.714
and then revive the patient
with an electric shock.

03:35.215 --> 03:36.634
People whose brains

03:36.675 --> 03:38.135
have all but ceased to function

03:38.177 --> 03:39.887
can still be kept alive.

03:41.639 --> 03:43.599
Cutting an organ out of one person

03:43.641 --> 03:45.768
and sewing it into the body of another,

03:45.809 --> 03:49.229
that's no longer a notion
out of Frankenstein.

03:51.649 --> 03:54.443
That's what medicine
has always been about...

03:54.485 --> 03:56.820
finding a way to eliminate suffering

03:56.862 --> 03:59.073
and keep death at bay,

03:59.114 --> 04:01.408
even though some early methods

04:01.450 --> 04:03.786
may now seem barbaric.

04:03.827 --> 04:05.621
No matter what the era,

04:05.663 --> 04:08.123
the question has always been,

04:08.165 --> 04:11.293
"How far are we willing to go

04:11.335 --> 04:13.587
to keep a loved one alive?"

04:17.132 --> 04:20.302
In 1883, George Brown found himself

04:20.344 --> 04:23.138
asking that very same question.

04:25.933 --> 04:29.061
Census records tell us that
Brown owned a small farm

04:29.103 --> 04:31.897
in the rural community
of Exeter, Rhode Island.

04:31.939 --> 04:33.732
He had a family, and, like most

04:33.774 --> 04:36.026
if not all of his neighbors,

04:36.068 --> 04:37.403
he was Protestant.

04:40.572 --> 04:43.325
These were people who prided
themselves on hard work,

04:43.367 --> 04:45.202
self-reliance,

04:45.244 --> 04:47.871
and perseverance in
the face of hardship.

05:49.767 --> 05:52.227
[COUGHING]

05:54.313 --> 05:56.774
[GASPING]

06:09.703 --> 06:10.829
[COUGH]

06:26.804 --> 06:29.348
This wasn't George
Brown's first encounter

06:29.389 --> 06:30.724
with the phantom killer.

06:30.766 --> 06:33.185
I'm sorry, George.

06:33.227 --> 06:35.938
You've seen how this ends.

06:35.979 --> 06:39.233
In 1883, consumption claimed the lives

06:39.274 --> 06:41.693
of one in four people in New England.

06:43.612 --> 06:46.907
His wife Mary Elizabeth
had contracted the disease

06:46.949 --> 06:49.993
and died an equally agonizing death.

06:51.245 --> 06:53.080
Now it would claim

06:53.122 --> 06:55.415
his oldest daughter Mary Olive.

06:55.457 --> 06:57.084
The newspaper wrote

06:57.126 --> 07:00.129
of the town's sorrow at her passing.

07:00.170 --> 07:02.840
The last hours she lived, they said,

07:02.881 --> 07:04.383
were a great suffering,

07:04.424 --> 07:05.843
yet her faith was firm,

07:05.884 --> 07:08.053
and she was ready for the change.

07:12.057 --> 07:14.393
George was not a religious man,

07:14.434 --> 07:17.271
but he prayed every night
that this terrible sickness

07:17.312 --> 07:19.690
would leave his children alone.

07:23.944 --> 07:25.737
We know from death records

07:25.779 --> 07:28.574
that consumption continued
to plague New Englanders.

07:30.450 --> 07:32.035
But for nine years,

07:32.077 --> 07:34.163
George's prayers were answered,

07:34.204 --> 07:35.998
and his family was spared.

07:47.342 --> 07:48.760
[GIGGLING]

07:48.802 --> 07:52.097
Edwin, turn yourself from the ladies.

07:52.139 --> 07:54.183
Yes, sir.

07:54.224 --> 07:56.435
You two have been married
for a whole year now.

07:56.476 --> 07:58.478
Aren't you sick of each other yet?

07:58.520 --> 08:00.814
[SIGH] With a little more work,

08:00.856 --> 08:03.859
there'll be more than just the
two of us by the first snow.

08:03.901 --> 08:05.611
[LAUGHING]

08:06.737 --> 08:08.447
[COUGHING]

08:18.540 --> 08:19.875
Let me see.

08:26.506 --> 08:28.050
How long?

08:28.091 --> 08:30.302
A couple of weeks.

08:31.887 --> 08:33.138
Do they know?

08:44.524 --> 08:47.027
No. I'll finish.

08:47.069 --> 08:48.111
Nurse yourself.

08:50.697 --> 08:52.032
Yes, sir.

09:02.960 --> 09:06.255
Thomas Brandt, from over in Providence,

09:06.296 --> 09:09.549
his brother took ill a few months back.

09:09.591 --> 09:10.801
They sent him

09:10.842 --> 09:13.387
to Colorado Springs.

09:13.428 --> 09:16.473
There's a special hospital
there for treatment.

09:16.515 --> 09:18.475
The mountain air clears
the lungs, they say.

09:18.517 --> 09:21.353
Did it work for Thomas' brother?

09:21.395 --> 09:24.439
Thomas says he's good as new.

09:26.441 --> 09:29.152
So we'll sell some heads of cattle.

09:29.194 --> 09:30.487
I can't let you do that.

09:30.529 --> 09:31.655
They're my cattle, son.

09:32.906 --> 09:35.867
Who will help you bring in the crop?

09:35.909 --> 09:37.160
I will.

09:37.202 --> 09:42.582
Your strong sister will.

09:42.624 --> 09:44.418
- You must go.
- You both go.

09:46.628 --> 09:47.838
Both of you.

09:50.257 --> 09:51.967
I've lost a wife.

09:52.009 --> 09:55.053
I've lost a daughter.
I won't lose a son.

10:09.484 --> 10:12.571
Three months after
Edwin left for Colorado,

10:12.612 --> 10:15.991
the phantom killer
returned to the Brown house.

10:30.589 --> 10:33.175
This time it came for Mercy.

10:39.264 --> 10:41.975
The pandemic had
reached epic proportions,

10:42.017 --> 10:45.729
and after enduring the ravages
of such a brutal disease,

10:45.771 --> 10:48.857
the last remaining shred
of hope was that death

10:48.899 --> 10:50.901
would finally bring relief.

10:56.239 --> 10:59.785
But only if the dead were actually dead.

11:10.670 --> 11:13.090
At this time in the late 19th century,

11:13.131 --> 11:17.969
pronouncing someone dead was
more guess work than science.

11:18.011 --> 11:22.015
The fear of premature burial
HAD A NAME: Tapephobia.

11:22.057 --> 11:25.852
And thus the birth of
the Waiting Mortuary,

11:25.894 --> 11:28.313
the place where the probably,

11:28.355 --> 11:32.484
but maybe not completely
dead could be observed.

11:32.526 --> 11:35.445
That is until the only
sure fire sign of death

11:35.487 --> 11:38.448
PRESENTED ITSELF: putrefaction.

11:38.490 --> 11:41.743
The best of the
establishments were adorned

11:41.785 --> 11:45.038
with huge floral arrangements
to mask the stench.

11:45.080 --> 11:48.750
Still, why wait that long
if you didn't have to?

11:48.792 --> 11:50.669
There were a growing
number of techniques

11:50.710 --> 11:54.005
that could provide a speedier verdict,

11:54.047 --> 11:57.717
like sticking a pin under the nail bed.

11:57.759 --> 12:01.930
Putting a live beetle in the ear.

12:01.972 --> 12:05.392
Bugle fanfares at point blank range.

12:05.434 --> 12:08.520
Razor cuts to the souls of the feet.

12:08.562 --> 12:11.898
A specially designed nipple pincer.

12:11.940 --> 12:15.610
Sticking a pencil up the nose.

12:15.652 --> 12:19.906
Once physician even developed a
hand cranked tongue-pulling machine.

12:19.948 --> 12:22.492
For those with sufficient means,

12:22.534 --> 12:24.202
there was another option,

12:24.244 --> 12:26.580
the safety coffin.

12:26.621 --> 12:28.457
Enterprising inventors,

12:28.498 --> 12:30.834
embracing the zeitgeist of the moment,

12:30.876 --> 12:32.502
proposed numerous patents

12:32.544 --> 12:35.881
for this emerging class
of mortuary product.

12:35.922 --> 12:39.259
One popular design
consisted of a long tube

12:39.301 --> 12:43.180
that provided light and fresh air.

12:43.221 --> 12:45.765
One doctor designed
a system using a bell.

12:45.807 --> 12:48.268
Strings were attached to the hands,

12:48.310 --> 12:50.312
feet, and head of the corpse,

12:50.353 --> 12:53.064
and if the bell rang,
the attendant would

12:53.106 --> 12:54.649
summon the gravediggers,

12:54.691 --> 12:56.651
who'd rapidly reverse their labor,

12:56.693 --> 13:00.697
freeing the occupant from
his terrifying predicament.

13:00.739 --> 13:04.784
Hence the expression,
"Saved by the bell."

13:07.204 --> 13:11.249
The thing is, we'll never know
just how many woke in terror

13:11.291 --> 13:13.460
only to die a second death.

13:17.506 --> 13:19.966
After several weeks in Colorado Springs,

13:20.008 --> 13:22.385
Edwin's health was improving.

13:22.427 --> 13:24.763
The therapies and fresh mountain air

13:24.804 --> 13:28.225
had reinvigorated his lungs.

13:28.266 --> 13:31.603
But, by the time Edwin came home,

13:31.645 --> 13:33.522
Mercy was dead.

13:37.609 --> 13:38.735
There we are.

13:44.824 --> 13:48.787
I should have been
there for her, for you.

13:48.828 --> 13:50.330
You know your sister.

13:50.372 --> 13:52.040
She didn't even want
to know she was sick.

13:52.082 --> 13:53.542
She knew you'd come home.

13:53.583 --> 13:55.710
She wanted you to stay and get well.

13:55.752 --> 13:57.170
You look well.

13:59.965 --> 14:01.925
Good to see you, son. Come on.

14:03.134 --> 14:04.511
[TICKING]

14:15.522 --> 14:16.898
[COUGHING IN DISTANCE]

14:33.290 --> 14:35.792
[COUGHING]

14:35.834 --> 14:37.252
Dr. Metcalf and some men are downstairs.

14:37.294 --> 14:38.503
They wish to speak with you.

14:44.801 --> 14:46.553
[COUGHS]

14:52.517 --> 14:54.144
George.

14:54.185 --> 14:55.645
Samuel.

14:57.188 --> 14:59.566
This is Mr. William Rose.

14:59.608 --> 15:01.109
He lives over in Peace Dale,

15:01.151 --> 15:03.194
but he is Exeter born and raised.

15:03.236 --> 15:05.989
Mr. Rose.

15:06.031 --> 15:09.993
I heard about the tragedy
that's befallen your family.

15:10.035 --> 15:12.871
That your son has taken
a turn for the worse.

15:15.999 --> 15:19.377
- I have a remedy.
- Are you a doctor?

15:19.419 --> 15:20.837
Most certainly not.

15:20.879 --> 15:24.049
He's just a farmer, just like us.

15:26.051 --> 15:28.637
But he has experience
with Eddie's illness.

15:28.678 --> 15:31.139
Samuel tells me your son found relief

15:31.181 --> 15:32.641
from his sickness out west.

15:34.225 --> 15:37.312
It wasn't until he came
home it started back?

15:37.354 --> 15:39.397
Yes.

15:39.439 --> 15:42.942
I believe the young man
is in the grip of a demon.

15:42.984 --> 15:46.404
George, do not listen to this.

15:46.446 --> 15:50.075
Well, if he keeps listening to
you, Eddie will die like the others.

15:50.116 --> 15:51.618
Now, we've heard about this, George.

15:51.660 --> 15:53.703
This... This demon,

15:53.745 --> 15:55.872
it... it gets into
the body of a loved one

15:55.914 --> 15:57.957
and it kills them,

15:57.999 --> 15:59.793
and it keeps reaching
back from the grave

15:59.834 --> 16:01.419
to feast on the blood of the next

16:01.461 --> 16:04.381
and the next until no one is left.

16:04.422 --> 16:09.010
William knows. He's seen it firsthand.

16:11.513 --> 16:14.516
I let my wife and
four of my children die

16:14.557 --> 16:17.018
before I accepted the truth.

16:17.060 --> 16:19.354
Until I did what I should
have done from the start.

16:21.064 --> 16:23.108
And what was that?

16:23.149 --> 16:28.029
Since the demon spirit resides
in the heart of the diseased,

16:28.071 --> 16:32.200
we must unearth their bodies
and find out which is the host.

16:32.242 --> 16:36.538
You are suggesting I dig
up my wife and my daughters?

16:36.579 --> 16:38.331
If the body is sufficiently desiccated,

16:38.373 --> 16:40.500
we'll know if it is truly dead.

16:40.542 --> 16:44.838
But if there remains an unnatural glow,

16:44.879 --> 16:46.756
we must check the heart...

16:46.798 --> 16:48.550
for blood.

16:48.591 --> 16:51.302
If present, we know the
demon has taken it as a host,

16:51.344 --> 16:52.595
and we must burn it.

16:52.637 --> 16:55.140
It's Old World superstition.

16:55.181 --> 16:57.934
Medieval folklore. We
live in the New World.

16:57.976 --> 17:00.311
Well, call it what
you want, but it works.

17:00.353 --> 17:03.857
It saved Mr. Rose and his daughter.

17:03.898 --> 17:07.609
She lives now with a family of her own.

17:07.652 --> 17:10.280
There are things on this
earth that we cannot explain,

17:10.320 --> 17:14.576
but that doesn't make
them any less possible.

17:14.617 --> 17:17.412
We can save your only son.

17:20.665 --> 17:22.541
I'm sorry for your loss, Mr. Rose.

17:22.584 --> 17:27.046
I'd like you to leave my house. Now.

17:29.299 --> 17:31.426
I'll escort them out.

17:31.468 --> 17:32.677
Please.

17:38.099 --> 17:39.309
Go on, Samuel.

17:56.075 --> 17:57.535
How much did you hear?

18:03.917 --> 18:07.629
I refuse to give into that madness.

18:10.757 --> 18:14.219
I'm not superstitious but this plague,

18:14.260 --> 18:18.515
this demon has taken so many,

18:18.556 --> 18:21.351
and now it wants Eddie.

18:25.855 --> 18:29.734
What if there's something
to what they're saying?

18:29.776 --> 18:31.569
- What if...
- Lily.

18:31.611 --> 18:32.779
If we do nothing, Eddie will die.

18:32.821 --> 18:34.072
We both know that.

18:37.659 --> 18:40.870
If what they're saying could work,

18:40.912 --> 18:44.040
I know that Mercy would want us to try.

18:44.082 --> 18:47.502
I didn't know the other
members of your family.

18:50.630 --> 18:52.590
Can we live with ourselves,

18:52.632 --> 18:56.135
if no matter how improbable?

18:58.137 --> 19:02.350
This could work. And
we didn't even try it.

19:06.938 --> 19:08.231
I don't know.

19:12.026 --> 19:13.152
Please.

19:16.698 --> 19:21.536
NARRATOR: George Brown was being
asked to do the unthinkable:

19:21.578 --> 19:24.122
exhume the bodies of his family to see

19:24.163 --> 19:28.167
if they were, in a way, still alive.

19:31.045 --> 19:32.755
It was a ritual with a name.

19:35.049 --> 19:38.094
Therapeutic exhumation.

19:38.136 --> 19:41.055
To ensure that the
dead were really dead.

19:41.097 --> 19:44.851
The idea was born some
hundred years earlier

19:44.893 --> 19:47.103
from the work of George Stahl,

19:47.145 --> 19:50.148
one of Germany's most respected doctors.

19:50.189 --> 19:52.609
Stahl was obsessed with understanding

19:52.650 --> 19:55.278
what separated life from death.

19:55.320 --> 19:57.488
He believed that an invisible life force

19:57.530 --> 20:00.408
flowed through the human body...

20:00.450 --> 20:02.785
and this force keeps
the lungs breathing,

20:02.827 --> 20:06.331
the heart beating, the blood liquid.

20:06.372 --> 20:09.167
He called that force the animus...

20:09.208 --> 20:12.086
the soul.

20:12.128 --> 20:14.380
Decomposition could only begin

20:14.422 --> 20:18.801
once the soul had left the body.

20:18.843 --> 20:22.555
But we now know that Stahl had it wrong.

20:22.597 --> 20:25.558
But people back then thought
it was cutting-edge science,

20:25.600 --> 20:29.103
and used it to justify
their own superstitions...

20:29.145 --> 20:33.441
that some souls remain in their corpses.

20:33.483 --> 20:35.360
And to sustain themselves,

20:35.401 --> 20:38.488
those souls feed on the living,

20:38.529 --> 20:42.367
spreading disease as they feast.

20:42.408 --> 20:46.579
This strange combination
of bad science and folklore

20:46.621 --> 20:49.415
was brought to America
by German Army surgeons

20:49.457 --> 20:53.336
who aided the British in
the American Revolution.

20:53.378 --> 20:56.255
When a town was plagued by Consumption,

20:56.297 --> 20:58.549
they would exhume the corpses.

20:58.591 --> 21:02.387
If they discovered flesh that
hadn't decomposed sufficiently

21:02.428 --> 21:04.931
or blood that hadn't coagulated,

21:04.973 --> 21:07.350
it could mean only one thing:

21:07.392 --> 21:11.896
the soul was still trapped in the body.

21:11.938 --> 21:16.859
The heart would be surgically
removed and cremated.

21:16.901 --> 21:21.030
Thus the soul would be put
to rest once and for all.

21:21.072 --> 21:23.741
And the living would be safe.

21:23.783 --> 21:27.203
[SCREAMING]

21:27.245 --> 21:29.956
[COUGHING]

21:29.998 --> 21:31.207
He awoke screaming.

21:31.249 --> 21:34.794
[GASPING, COUGHING]

21:34.836 --> 21:36.004
He's burning up.

21:36.045 --> 21:38.339
- [COUGHING]
- Shh, shh.

21:38.381 --> 21:40.842
- [GASPING]
- Eddie.

21:40.883 --> 21:42.844
Shh, shh.

21:42.885 --> 21:44.804
[GASPING]

21:50.435 --> 21:53.271
- Shh.
- [GASPING]

21:53.312 --> 21:55.857
[THUNDER]

21:57.066 --> 21:58.818
[COUGHS] Mercy!

22:01.029 --> 22:03.489
[GASPING, COUGHING]

22:08.828 --> 22:10.747
[PANTING]

22:20.840 --> 22:22.050
[COUGHING]

22:24.719 --> 22:26.512
[COUGHING]

22:26.554 --> 22:28.681
Stay with him.

22:30.183 --> 22:31.726
[COUGHING]

22:35.772 --> 22:37.648
[GROANING]

22:42.570 --> 22:45.490
♪♪

22:48.367 --> 22:50.286
[BANGING]

23:07.261 --> 23:09.180
[BANGING]

23:19.232 --> 23:21.150
[WIND BLOWING]

23:27.198 --> 23:29.117
[BANGING]

23:38.000 --> 23:40.920
♪♪

23:53.683 --> 23:55.601
[BANGING CONTINUES]

24:03.442 --> 24:04.694
[SQUEAKING]

24:06.904 --> 24:08.739
We are practical men,

24:08.781 --> 24:10.533
you and I. Aren't we?

24:14.078 --> 24:17.707
I don't believe in demons,
Harold. I know you don't.

24:17.748 --> 24:19.292
[CLEARS THROAT]

24:19.333 --> 24:21.169
After all I've lost, I
barely believe in God.

24:21.210 --> 24:23.629
God forgive me.

24:23.671 --> 24:27.133
But Rose claims this
remedy saved his daughter.

24:30.678 --> 24:34.182
Am I being... selfish

24:34.223 --> 24:36.184
not to at least allow them to try to

24:36.225 --> 24:37.602
bring Edwin some relief?

24:41.189 --> 24:43.316
The Germans discovered

24:43.357 --> 24:45.443
consumption is caused by bacteria.

24:45.484 --> 24:47.403
I don't care about the... the cause,

24:47.445 --> 24:48.821
I care about the remedy.

24:52.033 --> 24:53.492
They told us it was hereditary,

24:53.534 --> 24:55.995
now it's a bacteria?

24:56.037 --> 24:58.414
Next is a parasite.

24:58.456 --> 24:59.707
I don't know what to believe in.

25:02.501 --> 25:05.504
You cannot abandon your faith

25:05.546 --> 25:07.548
just because you've
fallen on hard times.

25:07.590 --> 25:10.259
That is what faith is there for.

25:10.301 --> 25:13.429
I know. That's true.

25:13.471 --> 25:16.307
But, at this point...

25:16.349 --> 25:19.143
[SIGHS]

25:19.185 --> 25:23.105
my belief is that
William Rose offers hope.

25:23.147 --> 25:25.399
False hope.

25:25.441 --> 25:26.734
He will fail, too.

25:26.776 --> 25:27.902
If he fails, he fails.

25:32.031 --> 25:36.577
But I'll know I've tried everything
in my power to save my boy.

25:36.619 --> 25:38.454
What are you willing to believe in

25:38.496 --> 25:40.665
if it makes you less human?

25:42.458 --> 25:43.876
Will they forgive me,

25:43.918 --> 25:46.295
my family, my neighbors?

25:49.507 --> 25:52.343
Could I forgive myself if I
didn't at least let them try?

25:52.385 --> 25:55.805
There's no medical science
to anything they are saying.

26:01.686 --> 26:03.104
You're a good friend, Harold.

26:03.145 --> 26:04.897
You're my only friend in this...

26:04.939 --> 26:06.649
a good doctor.

26:08.234 --> 26:12.697
But your medical science
has done... nothing.

26:14.907 --> 26:15.866
[SIGHS]

26:19.287 --> 26:22.081
NARRATOR: George Brown
lived in a strange time

26:22.123 --> 26:24.834
where scientific discoveries
were rapidly changing

26:24.875 --> 26:27.169
how people engaged with the world,

26:27.211 --> 26:29.463
and how they imagined the future.

26:29.505 --> 26:34.719
Science was producing miracles
on an unprecedented scale.

26:34.760 --> 26:37.763
♪♪

26:43.811 --> 26:47.064
And yet medicine still fell short.

26:50.318 --> 26:53.237
Doctors were often in the
dark when it came to knowing

26:53.279 --> 26:56.324
what caused the diseases
that were ravaging so many.

26:58.534 --> 27:03.372
Like the consumption that had
decimated George Brown's family.

27:03.414 --> 27:07.335
Though the bacterium that caused
the disease, M. Tuberculosis,

27:07.376 --> 27:09.462
had been discovered ten years earlier,

27:09.503 --> 27:13.758
as of 1892 there was still no cure.

27:13.799 --> 27:16.635
Which left plenty of room
for less scientific remedies

27:16.677 --> 27:20.222
to keep their iron grip on
people's practices and beliefs.

27:23.684 --> 27:27.688
Like the belief that a heart, long dead,

27:27.730 --> 27:31.609
could still exert some
sort of terrible power

27:31.650 --> 27:35.279
draining the life from the living.

27:35.321 --> 27:37.239
[HEART BEATING]

27:43.162 --> 27:47.833
WILLIAM: Now, any bodies we unbury
and find they have not rotted,

27:47.875 --> 27:50.169
then it's proof they
walk the earth at night.

27:53.297 --> 27:56.634
Who was the first taken?

27:56.675 --> 27:58.969
My wife, Mary Elizabeth.

28:00.471 --> 28:02.556
Then that's where we start.

28:05.518 --> 28:07.520
May God understand and guide us.

28:10.564 --> 28:13.484
♪♪

28:19.949 --> 28:21.075
[MAN GRUNTING]

28:35.965 --> 28:37.633
[WOOD CRACKING]

28:47.101 --> 28:50.688
♪♪

29:01.657 --> 29:02.992
SAMUEL: Mary Olive died next?

29:07.663 --> 29:10.583
♪♪

29:13.043 --> 29:14.170
[GRUNTING]

29:16.088 --> 29:18.007
[COUGHING]

29:20.843 --> 29:24.388
♪♪

29:30.811 --> 29:32.855
- You have your answer.
- METCALF: Yes.

29:34.231 --> 29:35.524
The answer is, this is over.

29:35.566 --> 29:36.901
You've seen for yourselves.

29:36.942 --> 29:38.027
Return them to their rest,

29:38.068 --> 29:40.279
and go back home to your families.

29:40.321 --> 29:41.322
Mercy.

29:41.329 --> 29:44.331
Mercy was alive when her
mother and sister died.

29:44.366 --> 29:45.409
It can't be her.

29:45.451 --> 29:47.661
But what if it is?

29:47.703 --> 29:49.330
She'll come for your boy.

29:49.371 --> 29:51.373
She'll come for our boys.

29:53.417 --> 29:54.376
We have to know.

29:57.338 --> 30:00.257
♪♪

30:20.528 --> 30:22.446
Three months,

30:22.488 --> 30:24.240
and yet her skin is fresh

30:24.281 --> 30:26.283
as if still taking nourishment.

30:26.325 --> 30:27.409
SAMUEL: She's not dead.

30:28.827 --> 30:30.412
Look at her.

30:30.454 --> 30:31.789
At night she lives.

30:31.830 --> 30:34.416
METCALF: The body was kept in the shed

30:34.458 --> 30:36.794
awaiting spring thaw for burial.

30:36.835 --> 30:39.171
The cold preserved her, not a folk tale.

30:39.213 --> 30:42.132
A demon would be smart to use her.

30:42.174 --> 30:44.260
She doesn't need to
crawl up from the ground.

30:48.389 --> 30:49.598
We have no choice.

30:51.392 --> 30:52.560
It must be done.

30:53.769 --> 30:56.063
Samuel.

30:56.105 --> 30:57.314
You will not touch her.

30:57.356 --> 30:59.775
Don't you understand?

30:59.817 --> 31:01.986
This is as much for her
sake as it is Eddie's.

31:07.032 --> 31:10.869
If you do this then
Mercy can rest in peace...

31:10.911 --> 31:11.954
and save your son.

31:19.169 --> 31:20.129
What do I do?

31:23.382 --> 31:24.800
Can you do it?

31:28.429 --> 31:31.348
♪♪

32:00.919 --> 32:02.838
[SAWING]

32:11.138 --> 32:13.057
[BONES CRACKING]

32:16.268 --> 32:19.688
The heart is where the demon lives.

32:19.730 --> 32:22.900
If we find fresh blood,

32:22.941 --> 32:24.193
we'll know she carries it.

32:40.250 --> 32:41.210
There.

32:43.587 --> 32:45.005
You see it?

32:45.047 --> 32:46.423
The blood is coagulated

32:46.465 --> 32:50.344
as it should be after
three months frozen.

32:50.386 --> 32:52.012
Then we can't take any chances.

32:52.054 --> 32:56.433
We must take the heart and the liver...

32:56.475 --> 32:57.434
to be certain.

33:18.205 --> 33:19.456
WILLIAM: Burn it.

33:23.502 --> 33:27.089
Then make a tonic of the
ashes and give it to Edwin.

33:27.131 --> 33:28.215
METCALF: A tonic?

33:28.257 --> 33:30.134
It's how I saved my daughter.

33:37.808 --> 33:40.728
♪♪

34:21.601 --> 34:24.521
♪♪

34:41.079 --> 34:42.998
[COUGHING]

34:44.625 --> 34:45.667
Take this.

34:45.708 --> 34:47.878
I can't. I can't.

34:52.632 --> 34:54.467
I could never, I...

34:54.510 --> 34:57.094
[COUGHING]

34:57.137 --> 34:58.138
Listen to me.

34:58.180 --> 35:00.766
[WHEEZING]

35:00.808 --> 35:03.060
If it offers even the
slightest hope of a cure,

35:03.101 --> 35:05.562
you know Mercy herself would
implore you to drink it.

35:05.604 --> 35:06.939
Please.

35:10.984 --> 35:13.612
If not for yourself,

35:13.654 --> 35:14.780
then for me.

35:20.160 --> 35:21.745
Come on, son.

35:21.787 --> 35:22.746
This is where we are.

35:24.039 --> 35:25.123
This is where we are.

35:29.461 --> 35:32.464
I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

35:33.298 --> 35:34.550
I know, I know.

35:39.805 --> 35:40.806
I'm sorry.

35:40.848 --> 35:42.766
[PANTING]

35:43.976 --> 35:44.977
Good job.

35:45.018 --> 35:47.563
[PANTING]

35:51.400 --> 35:53.610
NARRATOR: The family
waited for the impossible,

35:53.652 --> 35:56.780
and prayed for Edwin's recovery.

35:56.822 --> 35:59.741
♪♪

36:23.265 --> 36:25.976
But on May 2nd, 1892,

36:26.018 --> 36:29.104
almost two months after
drinking the tonic,

36:29.146 --> 36:31.440
Edwin Brown passed away.

36:31.481 --> 36:33.901
He was 24 years old.

36:33.942 --> 36:36.987
George had taken the extraordinary,

36:37.029 --> 36:39.948
some would say barbaric action,

36:39.990 --> 36:42.242
to save his child.

36:42.284 --> 36:44.286
And he'd failed.

36:44.328 --> 36:47.247
♪♪

36:52.669 --> 36:56.131
Newspapers condemned George
Brown and the people of Exeter

36:56.173 --> 36:59.384
as remnants of a less enlightened time.

36:59.426 --> 37:01.720
The articles mocked them for believing

37:01.762 --> 37:04.848
a monster could escape from the grave.

37:04.890 --> 37:07.517
And they gave that monster a name:

37:07.559 --> 37:08.602
The Vampire.

37:13.440 --> 37:17.861
The story became a tabloid
sensation around the world.

37:17.903 --> 37:21.615
A clipping was found among
the papers of a writer.

37:21.657 --> 37:24.826
THE WRITER'S NAME: Bram Stoker.

37:24.868 --> 37:27.704
And the book inspired by Mercy's tale,

37:27.746 --> 37:30.082
I'm sure you've already guessed that.

37:30.123 --> 37:31.124
Dracula.

37:31.166 --> 37:34.086
♪♪

37:40.258 --> 37:43.053
The vampire tale quickly
moved from the printed page

37:43.095 --> 37:44.513
to the Silver Screen.

37:49.017 --> 37:51.311
And it's never really gone away.

37:56.942 --> 37:59.152
It's more than a little ironic.

37:59.194 --> 38:00.862
In many ways,

38:00.904 --> 38:03.573
thanks to the efforts of her father,

38:03.615 --> 38:05.492
Mercy Brown,

38:05.534 --> 38:07.995
the first American vampire,

38:08.036 --> 38:09.955
is still alive...

38:09.997 --> 38:11.123
today.

